1
00:00:06,708 --> 00:00:09,750
-[rapid hoofbeats]
-[cart wheels rattling]

2
00:00:09,750 --> 00:00:11,625
♪

3
00:00:28,333 --> 00:00:31,500
[CAPTAIN] Are you sure, sir?
This is far enough?

4
00:00:32,041 --> 00:00:33,333
[DENKEN] It will do.

5
00:00:33,333 --> 00:00:36,416
I can make it
the rest of the way by myself.

6
00:00:36,625 --> 00:00:38,750
This is where
our journey must end,

7
00:00:38,958 --> 00:00:41,625
for my journey
continues on foot.

8
00:00:41,833 --> 00:00:45,333
If you're certain,
travel safe, sir.

9
00:00:45,333 --> 00:00:48,291
-[hoofbeats]
-[cart wheels rattling]

10
00:00:48,500 --> 00:00:50,291
♪

11
00:01:06,333 --> 00:01:09,166
[♪ opening theme song playing]

12
00:01:31,166 --> 00:01:37,750
BEYOND JOURNEY'S END

13
00:02:35,708 --> 00:02:37,625
30 YEARS AFTER THE DEATH
OF HIMMEL THE HERO,

14
00:02:37,833 --> 00:02:39,833
IN THE DRACHEN REGION, LOCATED
ON THE NORTHERN PLATEAU

15
00:02:53,625 --> 00:02:55,458
It's in ruins.

16
00:02:55,875 --> 00:02:58,875
Well, it takes time to rebuild
after a dragon attack.

17
00:02:59,083 --> 00:03:00,333
I didn't realize

18
00:03:00,333 --> 00:03:02,125
you guys had to deal
with dragons up here.

19
00:03:02,333 --> 00:03:04,583
The Plateau's fun never ends.

20
00:03:04,583 --> 00:03:05,875
It could be much worse,

21
00:03:05,875 --> 00:03:07,458
-you know.
-How.

22
00:03:07,458 --> 00:03:09,416
[FRIEREN]
When I traveled
with Himmel and the others,

23
00:03:09,625 --> 00:03:12,125
we were attacked
by a thunder of dragons.

24
00:03:13,166 --> 00:03:15,625
Can you even imagine
that many in one place?

25
00:03:15,833 --> 00:03:17,291
I'd rather not.

26
00:03:17,291 --> 00:03:19,833
Uh, just to clarify,

27
00:03:20,041 --> 00:03:22,041
do they not usually move
as a thunder?

28
00:03:22,583 --> 00:03:25,000
Was this village attacked
by a thunder?

29
00:03:25,208 --> 00:03:26,708
[MAYOR] Yes.

30
00:03:26,708 --> 00:03:28,916
Seems the beasts have made
a nearby forest their home.

31
00:03:29,125 --> 00:03:31,458
You three are our best shot
at defeating them.

32
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,291
"Normal" around here
isn't very normal.

33
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:36,208
Not normal at all.

34
00:03:44,291 --> 00:03:46,000
[men grunting]

35
00:03:54,750 --> 00:03:57,583
Your village is
past the point of saving.

36
00:03:57,583 --> 00:03:59,416
You should rebuild
somewhere new.

37
00:04:01,166 --> 00:04:02,458
How could we?

38
00:04:02,458 --> 00:04:04,583
As dangerous as it is,

39
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:06,333
this is our home.

40
00:04:06,916 --> 00:04:08,916
-[MAN 1] Incoming.
-[MAN 2] Let me help.

41
00:04:09,125 --> 00:04:10,708
[MAN 3] Need more hands?

42
00:04:12,708 --> 00:04:15,166
[FERN]
He's right, Mistress Frieren.

43
00:04:15,166 --> 00:04:17,750
That was a cruel thing to say.

44
00:04:17,958 --> 00:04:20,333
[STARK] Somebody's gotta
help these villagers.

45
00:04:20,541 --> 00:04:22,583
One dragon
is a challenge enough.

46
00:04:22,583 --> 00:04:24,208
To face a horde...

47
00:04:24,416 --> 00:04:26,416
We will not come out unscathed.

48
00:04:26,625 --> 00:04:29,750
We protect other people's homes,
don't we?

49
00:04:30,916 --> 00:04:33,416
It shall depend on the reward.

50
00:04:33,625 --> 00:04:36,333
Alas, our village
is extremely poor.

51
00:04:36,541 --> 00:04:38,583
I fear we have
nothing to pay you with.

52
00:04:38,791 --> 00:04:40,583
You don't have
a single grimoire?

53
00:04:40,791 --> 00:04:43,041
There's one,
but it's terribly useless

54
00:04:43,250 --> 00:04:45,125
and I doubt
it's of any interest to you.

55
00:04:45,333 --> 00:04:46,875
It allows you to say
tongue twisters

56
00:04:47,083 --> 00:04:48,500
without tripping
over your words.

57
00:04:48,708 --> 00:04:52,583
[FERN] Goodness, that does sound
terribly useless.

58
00:04:57,166 --> 00:05:00,166
At the end of the day,
a spell is still a spell.

59
00:05:00,375 --> 00:05:03,000
You mentioned
they live in a nearby wood?

60
00:05:03,458 --> 00:05:06,500
Yes, they're somewhere
in that forest up ahead.

61
00:05:07,291 --> 00:05:10,583
If we can pick up
even a trace of mana,

62
00:05:10,916 --> 00:05:12,625
we can track them down.

63
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:14,583
♪

64
00:05:36,875 --> 00:05:39,333
[FRIEREN]
Looks like we continue straight.

65
00:05:39,541 --> 00:05:41,833
I'm impressed
by your magic all the time.

66
00:05:42,041 --> 00:05:44,291
But when it's
so applicable like this,

67
00:05:44,291 --> 00:05:46,416
I'm reminded how amazing it is.

68
00:05:46,416 --> 00:05:49,291
Do you have
any more praise for me?

69
00:05:49,291 --> 00:05:50,625
You can't give in.

70
00:05:50,833 --> 00:05:52,333
No more careless praise.

71
00:05:52,541 --> 00:05:54,833
It's bad for Mistress Frieren's
development.

72
00:05:55,041 --> 00:05:56,875
[STARK]
Hm... I guess that's true.

73
00:05:56,875 --> 00:06:00,208
[FRIEREN] What exactly
do you two take me for?

74
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:04,583
If anyone still cares,
the dragons are this way.

75
00:06:04,583 --> 00:06:05,833
♪

76
00:06:39,916 --> 00:06:41,500
-[FRIEREN] There they are.
-[dragons snoring softly]

77
00:06:41,708 --> 00:06:43,125
[STARK]
That's a lot of dragons.

78
00:06:43,333 --> 00:06:45,208
[FRIEREN]
But luckily they're small.

79
00:06:45,416 --> 00:06:48,333
They won't be nearly as strong
as that solar dragon.

80
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:51,416
Regardless of size,
dragons are smart.

81
00:06:51,625 --> 00:06:53,125
Don't let them surround you.

82
00:06:53,833 --> 00:06:55,708
I say we draw them
to a single point

83
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:57,291
and take them down at once.

84
00:06:57,291 --> 00:06:58,583
Well, Stark?

85
00:06:58,791 --> 00:07:00,416
Think that you're up
for the job?

86
00:07:00,833 --> 00:07:03,625
You're an experienced
dragon fighter these days.

87
00:07:03,833 --> 00:07:05,125
Tall order.

88
00:07:05,125 --> 00:07:07,291
More like experienced bait.

89
00:07:08,750 --> 00:07:10,833
[dragon growls]

90
00:07:11,750 --> 00:07:13,041
Shall we begin?

91
00:07:13,041 --> 00:07:15,125
You better actually fire
some spells this time!

92
00:07:15,333 --> 00:07:17,125
♪

93
00:07:18,750 --> 00:07:21,458
If you slay them all first,
I won't have to.

94
00:07:23,333 --> 00:07:24,416
[Stark grunts]

95
00:07:25,208 --> 00:07:27,291
[dragons growling]

96
00:07:28,291 --> 00:07:29,458
[Stark grunting]

97
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:50,000
[Stark gasps]

98
00:07:50,208 --> 00:07:51,125
[dragon growling]

99
00:07:53,208 --> 00:07:54,833
♪

100
00:07:58,750 --> 00:07:59,833
[Stark grunting]

101
00:08:14,833 --> 00:08:16,416
[Stark grunts]

102
00:08:19,416 --> 00:08:20,500
[Stark groans]

103
00:08:30,916 --> 00:08:33,916
That job
was ridiculously intense.

104
00:08:34,125 --> 00:08:36,708
At least the village's church
wasn't destroyed.

105
00:08:36,916 --> 00:08:39,625
Mr. Stark, I watched
an angry dragon

106
00:08:39,833 --> 00:08:42,250
-chew on your head.
-[dragon grunting]

107
00:08:43,458 --> 00:08:45,958
[FERN] How are you
not in worse shape?

108
00:08:46,333 --> 00:08:47,833
[STARK] Uh...

109
00:08:49,416 --> 00:08:51,208
I got no clue.

110
00:08:51,416 --> 00:08:53,625
Eisen's head
was often chewed as well.

111
00:08:53,833 --> 00:08:56,458
Durable skulls must be
a normal warrior trait.

112
00:08:56,666 --> 00:09:00,291
Mistress, nothing about
Mister Eisen is normal.

113
00:09:00,500 --> 00:09:02,125
[MAYOR] It took some rummaging.

114
00:09:03,833 --> 00:09:05,916
But here's
the promised grimoire.

115
00:09:06,125 --> 00:09:08,625
Thank you
for protecting our village.

116
00:09:18,250 --> 00:09:20,500
I've noticed an odd tendency.

117
00:09:20,708 --> 00:09:22,041
Whenever we help someone out,

118
00:09:22,250 --> 00:09:24,916
you almost always
blindly demand payment.

119
00:09:25,291 --> 00:09:27,500
Because Himmel the Hero
did the same.

120
00:09:27,708 --> 00:09:29,125
That's surprising.

121
00:09:29,125 --> 00:09:32,208
Agreed. I imagined him
as the sort that would want

122
00:09:32,416 --> 00:09:33,875
to help others for free.

123
00:09:34,500 --> 00:09:36,208
Curious, huh?

124
00:09:36,416 --> 00:09:38,458
Used to confound me, too.

125
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,416
Thank you so much
for your help, sir.

126
00:09:41,625 --> 00:09:43,666
[WOMAN] I only wish
that there was some way

127
00:09:43,875 --> 00:09:45,666
for us to properly repay you.

128
00:09:45,875 --> 00:09:48,583
But as you can see,
our village is poor.

129
00:09:48,791 --> 00:09:50,375
Though we can't offer much,

130
00:09:50,583 --> 00:09:52,750
I do hope you'll take this.

131
00:09:53,541 --> 00:09:55,333
[EISEN]
I won't allow it, Himmel.

132
00:09:55,541 --> 00:09:57,875
We cannot accept their food.

133
00:10:00,958 --> 00:10:02,833
Is that a grimoire?

134
00:10:04,666 --> 00:10:06,333
[MAN] Uh, unfortunately not.

135
00:10:06,541 --> 00:10:08,750
It's a notebook we received
from a traveling merchant

136
00:10:08,958 --> 00:10:10,125
some time ago.

137
00:10:10,125 --> 00:10:12,000
We have no use for it.

138
00:10:12,208 --> 00:10:13,625
♪

139
00:10:19,125 --> 00:10:20,666
[scribbling]

140
00:10:21,875 --> 00:10:23,333
[FRIEREN]
I have a question, Himmel.

141
00:10:24,291 --> 00:10:26,583
Why demand payment
in exchange for our aid,

142
00:10:26,791 --> 00:10:28,875
when you don't care
what we receive?

143
00:10:29,250 --> 00:10:31,583
If they pay us,
they don't owe us anything.

144
00:10:31,791 --> 00:10:33,666
No favors and no praise.

145
00:10:34,500 --> 00:10:37,000
After all, we are
the party of heroes.

146
00:10:41,708 --> 00:10:44,083
We're meant to be
protectors of the people,

147
00:10:44,291 --> 00:10:46,750
not collectors
of gratitude and debt.

148
00:10:46,958 --> 00:10:48,666
We should give, not take.

149
00:10:48,875 --> 00:10:50,125
♪

150
00:10:52,875 --> 00:10:55,833
If the people we help
are indebted to us,

151
00:10:56,458 --> 00:10:59,875
then the only people that we're
truly serving are ourselves.

152
00:11:01,333 --> 00:11:02,541
You see?

153
00:11:02,541 --> 00:11:04,583
That's why even
the most ridiculous spells

154
00:11:04,791 --> 00:11:07,041
suffice as payment in my eyes.

155
00:11:07,833 --> 00:11:09,333
Noble.

156
00:11:10,833 --> 00:11:13,666
[FRIEREN] Now start thinking
of a good tongue twister.

157
00:11:14,166 --> 00:11:17,250
[FERN] I still think
you just want more grimoires.

158
00:11:17,458 --> 00:11:19,583
[STARK] Next time,
maybe you can ask for one

159
00:11:19,791 --> 00:11:22,208
that prevents dragons
from biting your head.

160
00:11:24,208 --> 00:11:27,125
EPISODE 37: HIMMEL'S MEMOIRS

161
00:11:27,333 --> 00:11:28,458
♪

162
00:11:29,041 --> 00:11:31,541
[EISEN]
What's your analysis, Frieren?

163
00:11:31,750 --> 00:11:33,083
Is it letting up?

164
00:11:34,041 --> 00:11:35,250
[FRIEREN] It still looks like

165
00:11:35,458 --> 00:11:37,541
we won't be able
to head out for a while.

166
00:11:37,750 --> 00:11:40,000
[EISEN]
That's some terrible luck.

167
00:11:40,208 --> 00:11:42,458
I can't believe
we're stuck here.

168
00:11:42,666 --> 00:11:44,708
I'm so bored, I could die.

169
00:11:44,916 --> 00:11:46,875
Blame the bottle ache,
not the boredom.

170
00:11:47,083 --> 00:11:48,125
[Himmel chuckles]

171
00:11:48,541 --> 00:11:50,416
♪

172
00:11:53,500 --> 00:11:56,000
Keep your spirits high,
my brave friends!

173
00:11:56,208 --> 00:11:57,708
We're on
a life-changing adventure

174
00:11:57,916 --> 00:11:59,500
to slay the Demon King.

175
00:11:59,500 --> 00:12:03,208
[EISEN] Yet we haven't been
able to adventure for days now.

176
00:12:03,416 --> 00:12:05,708
Adventures are about
more than fighting

177
00:12:05,916 --> 00:12:07,791
and wandering pebbled roads.

178
00:12:08,333 --> 00:12:10,250
Sometimes, an adventure
can be enduring

179
00:12:10,458 --> 00:12:12,458
a series
of dreadful days indoors.

180
00:12:12,666 --> 00:12:15,333
[EISEN] Dreadful is your word,
not ours.

181
00:12:15,583 --> 00:12:16,791
[Himmel gasps]

182
00:12:16,791 --> 00:12:19,541
[EISEN] What are you
thrashing about for?

183
00:12:19,750 --> 00:12:21,791
Has death come
to catch you, too?

184
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:22,875
[HIMMEL] Uh...

185
00:12:23,083 --> 00:12:24,500
[thunder rumbling]

186
00:12:24,708 --> 00:12:26,333
[HIMMEL] It's nothing.

187
00:12:26,541 --> 00:12:28,500
30 YEARS AFTER
THE DEATH OF HIMMEL THE HERO,

188
00:12:28,708 --> 00:12:30,916
BY LAKE KORRIDOR,
LOCATED ON THE NORTHERN PLATEAU

189
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,416
We've been waiting
around this city for a week

190
00:12:34,625 --> 00:12:36,958
and the weather still
hasn't gotten better.

191
00:12:44,875 --> 00:12:47,708
Will you be able
to ferry us across today?

192
00:12:47,916 --> 00:12:49,958
You must know the answer.

193
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:01,166
Though made of wood,
my boat is not a coffin.

194
00:13:02,791 --> 00:13:04,625
I suppose not.

195
00:13:06,958 --> 00:13:08,750
I've heard of storms
over oceans,

196
00:13:08,958 --> 00:13:11,583
but I didn't know
they can form over lakes, too.

197
00:13:11,791 --> 00:13:14,208
Lake Korridor
is the largest body of water

198
00:13:14,416 --> 00:13:15,833
in all the northern lands.

199
00:13:16,208 --> 00:13:18,791
It's larger than
some inland seas.

200
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:20,125
[STARK] I believe it.

201
00:13:20,125 --> 00:13:21,875
You can hardly make out
the far shore.

202
00:13:24,291 --> 00:13:25,750
Immense mountain ranges

203
00:13:25,750 --> 00:13:28,750
to both the east and the west
disrupt air currents,

204
00:13:28,958 --> 00:13:31,333
making this time of year
brutally stormy.

205
00:13:32,166 --> 00:13:34,583
It's not uncommon
for large, established ships

206
00:13:34,791 --> 00:13:36,291
to sink in this season.

207
00:13:36,500 --> 00:13:37,916
[FERN]
And because of the wind,

208
00:13:38,125 --> 00:13:40,333
there's no chance we can cross
with flying magic.

209
00:13:40,541 --> 00:13:41,833
[FRIEREN]
It would be difficult to fly

210
00:13:42,041 --> 00:13:43,750
to the other side
on a clear day.

211
00:13:43,958 --> 00:13:47,250
The distance to shore
is vaster than you think.

212
00:13:47,458 --> 00:13:49,333
[FRIEREN]
I might be able to make it.

213
00:13:49,708 --> 00:13:52,375
But skilled as you are,
you lack the mana.

214
00:13:52,750 --> 00:13:56,000
Perhaps we would be better off
venturing around the lake.

215
00:13:56,208 --> 00:13:58,791
[FRIEREN] We most certainly
would not be.

216
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:00,541
Wait, why?

217
00:14:00,541 --> 00:14:03,833
I told you about the mountains
to the east and the west.

218
00:14:04,041 --> 00:14:05,166
[muffled] Mmm.

219
00:14:05,375 --> 00:14:07,291
They're as mighty as the lake.

220
00:14:07,500 --> 00:14:08,708
Trying to barrel
our way through

221
00:14:08,916 --> 00:14:10,291
without so much
as a mountain pass

222
00:14:10,500 --> 00:14:11,625
to hang our hats on...

223
00:14:11,833 --> 00:14:12,750
[muffled] Mmm.

224
00:14:13,166 --> 00:14:14,750
...would be suicide.

225
00:14:14,958 --> 00:14:17,791
We should stay put and wait
for a few months.

226
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:19,750
It'll be leagues safer
and timelier

227
00:14:19,958 --> 00:14:22,458
than challenging the elements
head on with no plan.

228
00:14:23,208 --> 00:14:25,750
Fortunately, this is
a fairly large port city

229
00:14:25,958 --> 00:14:27,166
and trading hub.

230
00:14:27,166 --> 00:14:29,958
It's the perfect place
to pass the time.

231
00:14:32,750 --> 00:14:34,541
♪

232
00:15:12,250 --> 00:15:14,625
[STARK] One winter later
and here we are.

233
00:15:15,291 --> 00:15:16,625
Can you take us?

234
00:15:16,833 --> 00:15:17,875
Yes.

235
00:15:18,583 --> 00:15:21,125
But only if you're able to pay.

236
00:15:21,333 --> 00:15:23,416
Even though
the storms have passed,

237
00:15:23,625 --> 00:15:25,750
this voyage is not a safe one.

238
00:15:26,333 --> 00:15:28,458
The risk will need to be
worth it.

239
00:15:31,375 --> 00:15:33,291
That's almost offensive.

240
00:15:33,500 --> 00:15:37,125
We'd have the funds if someone
hadn't bought so many grimoires.

241
00:15:37,333 --> 00:15:39,208
Boredom took control.

242
00:15:39,958 --> 00:15:43,291
Fine. If you can't pay,
we'll exchange favors.

243
00:15:43,500 --> 00:15:46,000
On an island just offshore,

244
00:15:46,208 --> 00:15:48,083
there's an abandoned monastery.

245
00:15:48,291 --> 00:15:50,375
It's protected by a barrier.

246
00:15:50,708 --> 00:15:53,000
According to legend,
if you can get through,

247
00:15:53,208 --> 00:15:55,625
you'll find the memoirs
of Himmel the Hero.

248
00:15:56,250 --> 00:15:57,833
In my grandfather's time,

249
00:15:58,041 --> 00:16:01,083
Himmel the Hero saved our city
and its people.

250
00:16:01,708 --> 00:16:04,708
I've looked up to him
ever since I was a child.

251
00:16:05,458 --> 00:16:08,541
We've been starving
for those memoirs for ages.

252
00:16:08,750 --> 00:16:11,166
I'd like you
to find them for me.

253
00:16:11,708 --> 00:16:13,750
Himmel's memoirs, huh?

254
00:16:14,041 --> 00:16:15,708
Poor Himmel.

255
00:16:15,916 --> 00:16:17,791
All that work to record
your travels

256
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:19,916
just for the pages to slip away.

257
00:16:20,125 --> 00:16:22,833
Must have been
very disappointing.

258
00:16:25,916 --> 00:16:29,166
I can't believe they've been
hiding there this whole while.

259
00:16:29,708 --> 00:16:30,916
Sure.

260
00:16:31,125 --> 00:16:33,083
You've got yourself
a favor.

261
00:16:35,250 --> 00:16:36,375
♪

262
00:16:56,041 --> 00:16:58,250
It feels like
we're on the ocean.

263
00:16:58,458 --> 00:17:00,125
Is that a whole fleet of ships?

264
00:17:00,333 --> 00:17:01,541
Indeed.

265
00:17:01,541 --> 00:17:03,375
If you want to move people
or goods north,

266
00:17:03,583 --> 00:17:05,333
now is the best time to do it.

267
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,583
And the recent rumors
are playing a role.

268
00:17:08,791 --> 00:17:10,166
They say there's a Golden Land

269
00:17:10,375 --> 00:17:11,958
where things from streets
to rooftops

270
00:17:12,166 --> 00:17:13,625
are made of pure gold.

271
00:17:13,833 --> 00:17:14,958
More people are interested

272
00:17:15,166 --> 00:17:17,041
in crossing the lake
than normal.

273
00:17:17,250 --> 00:17:18,791
A Golden Land?

274
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:20,708
You think it really exists?

275
00:17:20,916 --> 00:17:22,583
[sailor chuckles] Who can say?

276
00:17:22,791 --> 00:17:24,541
All I know is
I've never met anyone

277
00:17:24,750 --> 00:17:26,500
who's actually been there.

278
00:17:26,708 --> 00:17:29,416
Probably just another tall tale.

279
00:17:32,500 --> 00:17:34,000
[SAILOR] There's the island.

280
00:17:46,791 --> 00:17:49,916
I was expecting the barrier
to be much stronger.

281
00:17:50,125 --> 00:17:52,791
In its defense,
it must be several decades old.

282
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:54,958
I bet this monastery was nice.

283
00:17:55,166 --> 00:17:57,375
Why would anybody abandon it?

284
00:17:57,833 --> 00:17:59,166
A monster attacked

285
00:17:59,166 --> 00:18:01,416
and the old roof couldn't
weather the damage.

286
00:18:01,625 --> 00:18:03,791
This place has been around
for a long while.

287
00:18:04,083 --> 00:18:05,541
That makes sense.

288
00:18:05,541 --> 00:18:08,541
And explains why they erected
the barrier in a hurry.

289
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:09,875
Mm, and why was that?

290
00:18:09,875 --> 00:18:12,291
Monasteries are known
to house books.

291
00:18:12,500 --> 00:18:15,750
Especially ones that are old,
valuable, and irreplaceable.

292
00:18:15,958 --> 00:18:17,416
[STARK] So, uh...

293
00:18:17,750 --> 00:18:19,416
[FERN]
So they put up the barrier

294
00:18:19,625 --> 00:18:22,416
to protect the books
they couldn't take with them.

295
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:26,791
That should do it.

296
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:29,041
Now, let's see what we can find.

297
00:18:31,541 --> 00:18:33,416
[FERN]
What happened to the monks?

298
00:18:33,625 --> 00:18:34,625
Where did they go?

299
00:18:35,375 --> 00:18:36,791
[SAILOR] Who knows?

300
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,083
It was abandoned ages ago.

301
00:18:39,291 --> 00:18:41,375
The only knowledge that remains
about this place

302
00:18:41,583 --> 00:18:44,416
is the legend
of Himmel the Hero's memoirs.

303
00:18:44,625 --> 00:18:45,833
[footsteps]

304
00:18:48,541 --> 00:18:50,250
[door creaks open]

305
00:18:54,541 --> 00:18:56,833
[STARK] This library is massive.

306
00:18:57,208 --> 00:18:59,708
[FERN] There's a statue
of Mr. Himmel.

307
00:19:00,041 --> 00:19:02,333
He nailed the pose
for that one.

308
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:04,541
[Fern gasps softly]

309
00:19:04,750 --> 00:19:05,875
♪

310
00:19:10,333 --> 00:19:12,041
[FRIEREN] Hello, book.

311
00:19:12,250 --> 00:19:13,583
Is it you?

312
00:19:13,791 --> 00:19:15,083
♪

313
00:19:17,541 --> 00:19:18,833
Yes.

314
00:19:19,041 --> 00:19:20,041
This is it.

315
00:19:20,250 --> 00:19:21,833
It's Himmel's handwriting.

316
00:19:23,083 --> 00:19:24,375
♪

317
00:20:21,375 --> 00:20:23,625
[FERN] What does it say?

318
00:20:25,125 --> 00:20:27,791
It's the tale
of a ridiculous journey.

319
00:20:30,916 --> 00:20:32,958
Just everyday minutiae.

320
00:20:35,041 --> 00:20:37,875
Here. I hope that you enjoy it.

321
00:20:38,083 --> 00:20:40,416
At last, our fare
is paid in full.

322
00:20:43,291 --> 00:20:45,875
I've heard plenty of stories
about the elven mage

323
00:20:46,083 --> 00:20:48,333
who traveled
with the party of heroes,

324
00:20:48,541 --> 00:20:50,375
but I never dreamed
I'd meet her.

325
00:20:51,208 --> 00:20:53,083
So, what gave it away?

326
00:20:53,375 --> 00:20:55,458
The wistful look
that came to your face

327
00:20:55,666 --> 00:20:57,375
when you skimmed over the book.

328
00:20:57,666 --> 00:21:00,000
I can tell that
it's important to you.

329
00:21:00,208 --> 00:21:01,708
You should keep it.

330
00:21:03,916 --> 00:21:05,958
There are plenty
of other valuable books

331
00:21:06,166 --> 00:21:07,458
tucked away in here.

332
00:21:08,166 --> 00:21:10,208
That's payment enough for me.

333
00:21:11,666 --> 00:21:14,041
Did it actually
show on my face?

334
00:21:14,333 --> 00:21:16,041
Only a little.

335
00:21:16,541 --> 00:21:17,791
[SAILOR] Let's be off.

336
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:20,500
We'll reach the far shore
before sunset.

337
00:21:25,291 --> 00:21:26,541
[FRIEREN] Mm...

338
00:21:26,750 --> 00:21:29,041
A collection of catchphrases.
[sighs]

339
00:21:29,250 --> 00:21:31,875
My! What a waste
of good pages.

340
00:21:32,083 --> 00:21:33,541
Hang on, I wanna try!

341
00:21:33,750 --> 00:21:35,791
"I hope you brought
your coin purse, beast.

342
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:39,541
For I, Stark the Warrior,
shall make you pay!"

343
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:43,250
[STARK] Uh...

344
00:21:43,750 --> 00:21:45,666
[SAILOR] It's a kraken!

345
00:21:45,875 --> 00:21:48,291
[STARK] There are
sea monsters in a lake?

346
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:50,166
[FRIEREN]
Your yelling provoked it.

347
00:21:50,375 --> 00:21:51,833
You're kidding!

348
00:21:52,041 --> 00:21:54,625
Think fast.
If we don't defeat it quickly,

349
00:21:54,833 --> 00:21:56,791
we shall all meet
a watery grave.

350
00:21:57,625 --> 00:22:00,041
-[FERN] Mistress Frieren!
-[STARK] Frieren!

351
00:22:01,875 --> 00:22:03,875
They're weak to well-placed
welts with...

352
00:22:04,083 --> 00:22:06,000
Hey! Huh?

353
00:22:06,208 --> 00:22:09,333
So, slaying a serpent is
as simple as it seems, sonny.

354
00:22:09,875 --> 00:22:11,291
I get it.

355
00:22:11,500 --> 00:22:12,916
She's picked now
to test her spell

356
00:22:13,125 --> 00:22:14,458
that allows you
to say tongue twisters

357
00:22:14,666 --> 00:22:16,000
without tripping
over your words.

358
00:22:16,208 --> 00:22:17,625
[STARK] Huh?

359
00:22:17,625 --> 00:22:19,708
Our lives are on the line
and you two are worried

360
00:22:19,916 --> 00:22:21,166
about tongue twisters?

361
00:22:21,375 --> 00:22:22,541
Creepy.

362
00:22:23,500 --> 00:22:26,083
[♪ closing theme song playing]

363
00:23:53,458 --> 00:23:55,666
[FRIEREN]
It's 3,000
-
meter drop.

364
00:23:55,875 --> 00:23:57,541
[FERN]
Mistress,
it's reacting to our mana.

365
00:23:57,750 --> 00:23:59,541
[HIMMEL]
If we defeat
the Demon King,

366
00:23:59,750 --> 00:24:02,041
a time will come when anyone
can enjoy this beautiful sight.

367
00:24:02,250 --> 00:24:03,458
EPISODE 38
THIS BEAUTIFUL SIGHT
